For the next fifty years Ald. 2 appears to have been the model edition. Little advance however was made on the J untine before Dionysius Lambinus. He dates his address to Oharles IX 1 November 1563 and afterwards speaks of his first edition as published in that year3 though the title-page of my copy has 1564. Lambinus was among the most illustrious of the great Latin scholars who studied and taught at Paris 111 the fifteenth century. His knowledge of Cicero and the older Latin writers as well as the Augustan poets has never been surpassed and

, rarely equalled. Whoever doubts that the nicest critical and gramma-

tical questions 0811 be expressed in Ciceronian Latin without effort or affectation, let him study the commentaries of Lambinus. Truly does Scaliger say of him ‘Latine et Romane loquebatur optimeque scribebat' : his ease and readiness fare astonishing. He made use he tells us of five mss: four of these appear to have been Italian mss. of the fifteenth century: the fifth, of which he used a collation by Turnebus and which he calls the Bertinian, was the same as the Leyden quart0. In his preface and throughout the work he acknowledges his obligations to Turnebus and Auratus. His Lucretius is perhaps the greatest of his works: there was more to be done here, and therefore he has done more. He had moreover a peculiar admiration for this author, of whom in the preface to his third edition he says ‘omnium poetarum Latinorum qui hodie exstant et qui ad nostram aetatem pervenerunt elegantissimus 811 purissimus, idemque gravissimus atque ornatissimus Lucretius est'. Though his boast that he has restored the text in 800 places goes beyond the truth‚ yet the superiority of his text over all preceding texts can scarcely be exaggerated 3 for the quickness of his 111118118011 united with his exquisite knowledge of the language gave him great power in the field of conjecture, and for nearly three centuries his remained the stand- ard text.
